
# <type>(<scope>): <subject>
#
# [optional body: explain what and why, wrapped at 72 columns]
#
# ---- Commit conventions for this repository ----
# Format: Conventional Commits 1.0.0, written in English.
#
# type:  feat | fix | docs | refactor | chore | test | ci
#
# For distributable skills under skills/<catalog>/<skill-name>/, choose the
# type by effect across SKILL.md, references, assets, and scripts:
#   fix      -> correct wrong, misleading, overly restrictive, or overly
#               permissive installed behavior (even when quality improves)
#   feat     -> add a new installed capability, branch, or workflow
#   refactor -> restructure without changing installed behavior
#   docs     -> supporting docs only (README, knowledge, or explanatory text
#               that does not change an installed skill)
# Markdown is a file format, not a reason to use docs.
# Test fix before feat: correcting existing behavior takes precedence over the
# fact that the result is an improvement.
#
# scope: the name(s) of the modified skill(s).
#   - one skill        -> feat(skill-authoring): add scaffold checklist
#   - several skills   -> fix(knowledge-sync, skill-authoring): align paths
#   - no specific skill, or a sweeping change across many skills
#                      -> omit the scope: chore: update catalog layout
#
# subject: imperative mood, no trailing period.
#
# Use a body when the change needs context (why, trade-offs, follow-ups);
# a subject line alone is fine for small, self-explanatory changes.
